[2]
Date: Thu, 23 Dec 2004 16:58:22 +0900 (JST)
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-12/23/content_2371905.htm>

Vietnam faces new bird flu outbreaks
------------------------------------
Vietnam has -- since early December 2004 -- detected new outbreaks of bird
flu in 6 southern localities, which have either killed or led to forced
culling of nearly 11 000 fowl, local newspaper reports Thursday quoted the
Department of Animal Health as saying.
At a conference on strengthening anti-bird flu activities held on
Wednesday, the department's director Qui Quang Anh said outbreaks occurred
in 7 wards and communes in Can Tho city and the provinces of Bac Lieu, Long
An, Tra Vinh, Hau Giang and Binh Phuoc between 1 and 20 Dec 2004, killing
and leading to the forced culling of 3840 chickens, 3815 ducks and 3000 quails.
Samples from dead fowls were tested positive to the bird flu virus strain
of H5, he noted.
The bird flu situation is getting serious, since Vietnam discovered only
one outbreak last month, and the country is facing potential outbreaks in
the northern region this winter whose cold weather favors the disease's spread.
"We must closely follow the situation on a daily basis. The busy transport
and big sales of poultry during the Lunar New Year Festival (in early
February 2005) plus complex weather may result in outbreaks in the northern
region," Anh said.
Now localities nationwide are beefing up anti-bird flu activities, mainly
by disinfecting affected areas, monitoring the transport of poultry and
their eggs, taking samples from fowls in high-risk provinces for virus
testing, and raising public awareness of the disease nationwide.
In late March 2004, Vietnam declared an end to the bird flu that had killed
17 percent of its poultry population and claimed 16 human lives during the
previous outbreak starting in December 2003. A total of 43.2 million fowl
nationwide either died or were culled, causing direct losses of 1.3
trillion Vietnamese dong (USD 82.8 million) to the local poultry industry.
